      "content": "No need to apologize, and don't worry about the trap analogy; the goblins are just very hungry and need to be fed with clear numbers, not confusing stories. Here is the exact math you need to crush that exam question:\n\n1.  **Calculate the Depreciable Base:** Subtract the salvage value from the cost.\n    *   $50,000 (Cost) - $5,000 (Salvage) = **$45,000**\n    *   *Think of this as the total amount of \"goblin food\" you have to distribute.*\n\n2.  **Divide by Useful Life:** Spread that amount evenly over the 5 years.\n    *   $45,000 / 5 years = **$9,000 per year**\n\nSo, your annual straight-line depreciation expense is **$9,000**. Every single year, you record a $9,000 expense, and by the end of year 5, your book value will be exactly the $5,000 salvage value, leaving no crumbs for the goblins to steal. Good luck with your exam!",
